body:

Anakin: Hey, that’s for believing in me, guys, from now on, I’ll never be too good or too evil again. I’m just gonna be me.

Rex: Do you think you can be a little less evil than that?

Anakin: Hmm, I dunno, do you think you could survive a fall out of the ship?

Ahsoka: Lol, good old Anakin again.

title: Star Wars
body:
The Star Wars trilogies all have a different target audience, whether or not these were the intended target audiences:

  • Originals: Men
  • Prequels: Kids
  • Sequels: Women

Original Trilogy: Men

When it was released, men were the overwhelming majority of Sci Fi creators and consumers.

There were only two strong female characters in these movies, one of whom we barely saw while the other eventually got stuffed into a classic Sci Fi bikini.

Prequel Trilogy: Kids

George Lucas tried to make these films appeal to everyone, which spread the plot much too thin and kept it from having a consistent tone.

The first movie in this trilogy was about a literal kid, and all three had Jar Jar Binks.

Padme’s strength and potential was underutilized, even though she was arguably the most interesting character.

Anakin himself was happy and easy-going. He didn’t have that Darth Vader edge, which decreased his appeal to Darth Vader fans.

The tone of the movies was too lighthearted to do justice to the dark heartbreak that should have been Vader’s rise, but children do not care about nuance so long as movies have silly moments, lightsaber fights, and explosions.

Sequel Trilogy: Women

Rey, Leia, Rose, Amilyn Holdo, Phasma, Jessika Pava, Korr Sella, Kaydel Ko Connix, Tallie Lintra. The amount of strong female characters is roughly equal to the strong male characters, and the top two leaders of the Resistance are women.

Adam Driver has mad skills with showing emotional vulnerability, which is like catnip for ladies.

Poe Dameron is so charming that, every time he looks at another character, we get ten new fanfics with that pairing.

Finn is the sweet, gentle guy you want to bring home to mom.

But mostly: women repeatedly kicking ass, continuing the great and noble legacy of our favorite princess.

Disclaimer: People outside the target audience can like any of these movies and be huge fans, and people within the target audience can hate them. This is not a 100% rule.

  • Sequels: Women

blog.description: I am a descriptivist linguist for the Mando'a language. I show what it can do, not what it MUST do. This is a place for discussion about Mando'a, and Mandalorian society and culture. Feel free to use the head cannons from this blog (or reblogged from others) in your RP or writing.
